## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation

Your code uses three APIs removed in .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) — all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`. The pattern is **timeout enforcement**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload for new callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // external cancellation — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation — the only model in modern .NET |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable wait (.NET 6+ API) |

### ⚠️ Critical pitfall: uncooperative work

The **fundamental limitation** of cooperative cancellation is that `Func<T> work` must voluntarily check for cancellation. If `work` is a long-running CPU-bound loop or a blocking call (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O), cancellation won't interrupt it — the task keeps running in the background.

**If `work` can cooperate**, refactor it to accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — token checked inside the loop
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // do incremental work
    }
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**If `work` cannot be modified** (third-party, native call), the task will continue running after timeout. The `TimeoutException` is still thrown to the caller, but the orphaned work leaks. For true hard-kill semantics, move the work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()`.

### Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` / `ThreadAbortException`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- ✅ Async overload provided for new callers
- ✅ External cancellation distinguished from timeout
